4. Input Validation & Control Flow
The do-while loop guarantees the menu is displayed at least once and continues until exit.
The switch-case construct routes each valid choice to the appropriate function.
The default case handles invalid menu inputs by displaying an error message.
Boundary checks (count >= 100) prevent array overflow in addPatient().

5. Queue for Waiting List
The STL queue<int> is used to enqueue each new patient's ID upon registration. 
This models real-world hospital waiting behavior where patients are served in the order of arrival (FIFO).
While the current implementation stores IDs in the queue, this can be extended to process patients 
(e.g., call the next patient) using queue front() and pop() operations.

6. Deletion Strategy
When a patient record is deleted, all subsequent elements in the array are shifted one position to the left to fill the gap. 
This maintains a compact, contiguous array without holes. The count is then decremented. 
This O(n) shift approach is appropriate for the small data size (max 100 patients) in this system.

